# -*- encoding: utf-8 -*-
# Arc: Other | Scene: CallshureSiege
# Source: C:\Program Files (x86)\Steam\steamapps\common\The Survival of Sarah Rose\game\script.rpy

translate ru strings:

    old "She would not meet with the Tribesman. She could not afford to lose the time preparing for a siege."
    new "She would not meet with the Tribesman. She could not afford to lose the time preparing for a siege."

    old "On Sarah's order, her army had begun preparing the siege weapons that she had brought with her from Rahayal."
    new "On Sarah's order, her army had begun preparing the siege weapons that she had brought with her from Rahayal."

    old "Her men moved swift, unpacking the wagons and transforming them into functional trebuchets."
    new "Her men moved swift, unpacking the wagons and transforming them into functional trebuchets."

    old "Sarah watched as the engineers ran through the last few checks, making sure the machines were ready."
    new "Sarah watched as the engineers ran through the last few checks, making sure the machines were ready."

    old "In the distance, she could see the city of Calshure. Its walls, solid, but not unyielding."
    new "In the distance, she could see the city of Calshure. Its walls, solid, but not unyielding."

    old "She remembered the walls of Bagrad."
    new "She remembered the walls of Bagrad."

    old "By comparison, these could hardly be called walls."
    new "By comparison, these could hardly be called walls."

    old "She had broken that city. She would break this one all the same."
    new "She had broken that city. She would break this one all the same."

    old "Still, it felt different."
    new "Still, it felt different."

    old "Different because unlike in Bagrad, this city was home to her own people."
    new "Different because unlike in Bagrad, this city was home to her own people."

    old "Every blow she would deliver would be one dealt to her own people."
    new "Every blow she would deliver would be one dealt to her own people."

    old "She wished there had been another way."
    new "She wished there had been another way."

    old "But she reminded herself that no throne was ever won without bloodshed."
    new "But she reminded herself that no throne was ever won without bloodshed."

    old "She had accepted it when she crossed the sea. Now she had to remain true in her resolve."
    new "She had accepted it when she crossed the sea. Now she had to remain true in her resolve."

    old "Are we nearly ready?"
    new "Are we nearly ready?"

    old "The engineer nodded."
    new "The engineer nodded."

    old "Yes, Commander. On your order."
    new "Yes, Commander. On your order."

    old "Sarah looked at the walls of Calshure again."
    new "Sarah looked at the walls of Calshure again."

    old "She could spot small figures walking along the ramparts of the wall."
    new "She could spot small figures walking along the ramparts of the wall."

    old "Either Tribesman or City Guard, forced to fight on behalf of the Tribesman."
    new "Either Tribesman or City Guard, forced to fight on behalf of the Tribesman."

    old "She hoped her army would limit the damage to her own people, but she also knew that war was never so precise."
    new "She hoped her army would limit the damage to her own people, but she also knew that war was never so precise."

    old "Sarah studied the land."
    new "Sarah studied the land."

    old "A small distance between her camp and the city."
    new "A small distance between her camp and the city."

    old "Out of reach from arrows, but not out of reach from her own trebuchets and catapults."
    new "Out of reach from arrows, but not out of reach from her own trebuchets and catapults."

    old "Break the walls, then advance and seize on the breach."
    new "Break the walls, then advance and seize on the breach."

    old "Close the gap fast enough so the Trbiesmen would not meet them on open fields, where their army would be strongest."
    new "Close the gap fast enough so the Trbiesmen would not meet them on open fields, where their army would be strongest."

    old "Fight them in the narrow streets of Calshure, where their horses would be useless."
    new "Fight them in the narrow streets of Calshure, where their horses would be useless."

    old "Across the field, more snow drifted down, blanketing the land."
    new "Across the field, more snow drifted down, blanketing the land."

    old "Her army was ready."
    new "Her army was ready."

    old "A heavy silence loomed over the field. Two armies, waiting with bated breath for the next moment."
    new "A heavy silence loomed over the field. Two armies, waiting with bated breath for the next moment."

    old "Suddenly, a thought came to her."
    new "Suddenly, a thought came to her."

    old "The Tribesmen were skilled warriors."
    new "The Tribesmen were skilled warriors."

    old "They knew better than anyone their own strengths."
    new "They knew better than anyone their own strengths."

    old "Were they truly so foolish as to surrender that by hiding behind walls?"
    new "Were they truly so foolish as to surrender that by hiding behind walls?"

    old "Commander? Are we ready?"
    new "Commander? Are we ready?"

    old "Or was she just seeing ghosts."
    new "Or was she just seeing ghosts."

    old "Wasting precious time while reinforcement from the Capital could already be on its way."
    new "Wasting precious time while reinforcement from the Capital could already be on its way."

    old "If they arrived during her attack...disaster."
    new "If they arrived during her attack...disaster."

    old "Sarah quickly decided."
    new "Sarah quickly decided."

    old "Start the siege"
    new "Start the siege"

    old "Fire!"
    new "Fire!"

    old "Sarah cried out her command."
    new "Sarah cried out her command."

    old "All as one, the engineers working the siege engines, released the ropes that were holding back their awesome force."
    new "All as one, the engineers working the siege engines, released the ropes that were holding back their awesome force."

    old "The wooden beams creacked loudly as the weight pulled them down, the pivotal force swinging the massive boulders off the ground."
    new "The wooden beams creacked loudly as the weight pulled them down, the pivotal force swinging the massive boulders off the ground."

    old "With a loud thud, the trebuchets released their deadly cargo."
    new "With a loud thud, the trebuchets released their deadly cargo."

    old "Sarah watched as the impossibly large boulders flew through the air as if they weighed nothing."
    new "Sarah watched as the impossibly large boulders flew through the air as if they weighed nothing."

    old "Soared through the air towards the city of Calshure."
    new "Soared through the air towards the city of Calshure."

    old "For a brief moment, there was still a quitness just before the boulders landed."
    new "For a brief moment, there was still a quitness just before the boulders landed."

    old "Then. The impact."
    new "Then. The impact."

    old "Sarah watched as the giant stones slammed into their targets."
    new "Sarah watched as the giant stones slammed into their targets."

    old "A loud thundering crack, like a splitting log, roaring out over the open field."
    new "A loud thundering crack, like a splitting log, roaring out over the open field."

    old "Sarah saw dust rise up from the impact, stone walls already damaged in places."
    new "Sarah saw dust rise up from the impact, stone walls already damaged in places."

    old "Most had found their targets, but some seemed to have gone over, landing into the city proper."
    new "Most had found their targets, but some seemed to have gone over, landing into the city proper."

    old "Sarah shuddered to think of the terrified citizens, huddled in their houses, suffering this siege."
    new "Sarah shuddered to think of the terrified citizens, huddled in their houses, suffering this siege."

    old "Reload and fire again!"
    new "Reload and fire again!"

    old "She yelled out her command, and the engineers quickly repeated their tasks."
    new "She yelled out her command, and the engineers quickly repeated their tasks."

    old "In no time at all, they had prepared a new salvo."
    new "In no time at all, they had prepared a new salvo."

    old "Again, Sarah watched as the stones struck the city of Calshure."
    new "Again, Sarah watched as the stones struck the city of Calshure."

    old "More and more, the walls crack and crumbled under the assault."
    new "More and more, the walls crack and crumbled under the assault."

    old "Calshure was a large town, but it had never been build to properly resist a real siege."
    new "Calshure was a large town, but it had never been build to properly resist a real siege."

    old "Keep firing until a breach opens up!"
    new "Keep firing until a breach opens up!"

    old "Again and again, on her orders, the boulders rained from the sky."
    new "Again and again, on her orders, the boulders rained from the sky."

    old "And though with each salvo, the walls crumbled more, Sarah also knew that each time a few kept missing."
    new "And though with each salvo, the walls crumbled more, Sarah also knew that each time a few kept missing."

    old "Each time, some poor family suffered a tragedy."
    new "Each time, some poor family suffered a tragedy."

    old "Then, uttering her last command to fire the trebuchets, Sarah saw the wall break."
    new "Then, uttering her last command to fire the trebuchets, Sarah saw the wall break."

    old "First slowly, then as the structural integrity gave way, the thing collapsed all at once."
    new "First slowly, then as the structural integrity gave way, the thing collapsed all at once."

    old "The broken and shattered wall flowed down like an avalanche, opening up a breach."
    new "The broken and shattered wall flowed down like an avalanche, opening up a breach."

    old "Attack!!!"
    new "Attack!!!"

    old "Sarah screamed as loudly as she could and her army sprung into motion."
    new "Sarah screamed as loudly as she could and her army sprung into motion."

    old "Already in formation, they began to advance quickly across the open field."
    new "Already in formation, they began to advance quickly across the open field."

    old "As they neared the city of Calshure, they came into range of the archers."
    new "As they neared the city of Calshure, they came into range of the archers."

    old "They were mostly City Guards, forced to fight. Their aim was poor, either by lack of practice or because they didn't want to fight."
    new "They were mostly City Guards, forced to fight. Their aim was poor, either by lack of practice or because they didn't want to fight."

    old "Either way, even they could not miss every shot."
    new "Either way, even they could not miss every shot."

    old "Sarah heard the screams as she advanced in the central column towards the breach in the wall."
    new "Sarah heard the screams as she advanced in the central column towards the breach in the wall."

    old "Move up into the breach, seize the ramparts!"
    new "Move up into the breach, seize the ramparts!"

    old "Sarah yelled out her commands, as much as it made a difference in the growing chaos of war."
    new "Sarah yelled out her commands, as much as it made a difference in the growing chaos of war."

    old "Plans only ever lasted so long, she thought as her heart began to pound harder in her chest."
    new "Plans only ever lasted so long, she thought as her heart began to pound harder in her chest."

    old "She watched the first units move up the shattered wall."
    new "She watched the first units move up the shattered wall."

    old "The broken stones shifted and moved like gravel under their feet, throwing them off balance."
    new "The broken stones shifted and moved like gravel under their feet, throwing them off balance."

    old "At the top, the Tribesmen guarded the small opening, taking advantage of the fact that their smaller numbers were less of an issue on such a small front."
    new "At the top, the Tribesmen guarded the small opening, taking advantage of the fact that their smaller numbers were less of an issue on such a small front."

    old "Still, she saw the first blows being traded."
    new "Still, she saw the first blows being traded."

    old "Her men began to push back the Tribesmen, taking hold of the breach."
    new "Her men began to push back the Tribesmen, taking hold of the breach."

    old "More and more of her men rushed up into the opening, entering the city of Calshure itself."
    new "More and more of her men rushed up into the opening, entering the city of Calshure itself."

    old "Sarah herself finally managed to join them, rushing up the broken pieces of wall and taking to the rampart."
    new "Sarah herself finally managed to join them, rushing up the broken pieces of wall and taking to the rampart."

    old "As she pulled herself up the last ledge, she climbed onto the top of the wall and looked out over the city."
    new "As she pulled herself up the last ledge, she climbed onto the top of the wall and looked out over the city."

    old "Smoke and ashes climbed up to the sky from the houses that had been struck by her siege engines."
    new "Smoke and ashes climbed up to the sky from the houses that had been struck by her siege engines."

    old "A few fires, here and there."
    new "A few fires, here and there."

    old "But the city seemed mostly unharmed. Or as much as it could be, given the circumstances."
    new "But the city seemed mostly unharmed. Or as much as it could be, given the circumstances."

    old "Down in the streets, Sarah saw fighting."
    new "Down in the streets, Sarah saw fighting."

    old "Her own men, clashing with the City Guard, who seemed almost eager to thrown down their weapons and surrender."
    new "Her own men, clashing with the City Guard, who seemed almost eager to thrown down their weapons and surrender."

    old "In other parts, a few Tribesmen, fighting to the death with not a hint of fear."
    new "In other parts, a few Tribesmen, fighting to the death with not a hint of fear."

    old "Sarah counted them."
    new "Sarah counted them."

    old "Her eyes narrowed."
    new "Her eyes narrowed."

    old "Where were they? This couldn't be all of them."
    new "Where were they? This couldn't be all of them."

    old "The thought came to her only a moment before she heard the deadly war cries of the Tribesmen."
    new "The thought came to her only a moment before she heard the deadly war cries of the Tribesmen."

    old "For a moment, Sarah was confused. The direction seemed impossible."
    new "For a moment, Sarah was confused. The direction seemed impossible."

    old "It wasn't coming from the city...but."
    new "It wasn't coming from the city...but."

    old "Sarah spun around."
    new "Sarah spun around."

    old "Still atop the wall, she could look out over the entire battlefield."
    new "Still atop the wall, she could look out over the entire battlefield."

    old "Her own army, still gathered around the breach of the wall, trying to enter the city, had left most of its flank unguarded."
    new "Her own army, still gathered around the breach of the wall, trying to enter the city, had left most of its flank unguarded."

    old "And there, rushing across the open fields, the core of the Tribesmen army attacked their rear."
    new "And there, rushing across the open fields, the core of the Tribesmen army attacked their rear."

    old "They had left the city, Sarah realized only now."
    new "They had left the city, Sarah realized only now."

    old "They had pretended to defend it from the walls, only to sneak out of the city from the other side, and flank them."
    new "They had pretended to defend it from the walls, only to sneak out of the city from the other side, and flank them."

    old "Of course, they would not have surrendered their most powerful advantage. Their cavalry."
    new "Of course, they would not have surrendered their most powerful advantage. Their cavalry."

    old "Sarah shuddered as she watched the Tribesmen cavalry charge strike into the rear of her forces."
    new "Sarah shuddered as she watched the Tribesmen cavalry charge strike into the rear of her forces."

    old "There, at the back, were mostly archers and lightly armored footmen."
    new "There, at the back, were mostly archers and lightly armored footmen."

    old "The Tribesmen cut through them as if they were nothing."
    new "The Tribesmen cut through them as if they were nothing."

    old "Her army, caught by surprise as much as herself, was in shock."
    new "Her army, caught by surprise as much as herself, was in shock."

    old "The Tribesmen charge cut deep into her army's core, slaughtering soldiers with blade and stomping hooves."
    new "The Tribesmen charge cut deep into her army's core, slaughtering soldiers with blade and stomping hooves."

    old "Most of her soldiers, so focussed on the breach, died without ever realizing the attack."
    new "Most of her soldiers, so focussed on the breach, died without ever realizing the attack."

    old "Their attacking from the rear!"
    new "Their attacking from the rear!"

    old "Sarah screamed out her orders, but in the midsts of the chaos, it was pointless."
    new "Sarah screamed out her orders, but in the midsts of the chaos, it was pointless."

    old "Too far up, she could do nothing to aid her own soldiers."
    new "Too far up, she could do nothing to aid her own soldiers."

    old "She could only watch them being slaughtered."
    new "She could only watch them being slaughtered."

    old "As the Tribesmen cut deeper into her army, the screaming of her soldiers grew louder and louder."
    new "As the Tribesmen cut deeper into her army, the screaming of her soldiers grew louder and louder."

    old "Each time a Tribesmen raised his blade and let it fall, another life ended."
    new "Each time a Tribesmen raised his blade and let it fall, another life ended."

    old "Like mad butchers, they ended hundreds."
    new "Like mad butchers, they ended hundreds."

    old "As the panic spread across her army, everyone seemed to slowly realize the situation."
    new "As the panic spread across her army, everyone seemed to slowly realize the situation."

    old "The Tribesmen's mad charge was slowing down, having lost their initial momentum and finding more bodies in their way."
    new "The Tribesmen's mad charge was slowing down, having lost their initial momentum and finding more bodies in their way."

    old "The damage they were doing was still immense, but by now they slowed into a melee."
    new "The damage they were doing was still immense, but by now they slowed into a melee."

    old "Skilled warriors, even here the Tribesmen proved their reputation to be true."
    new "Skilled warriors, even here the Tribesmen proved their reputation to be true."

    old "But with each passing moment, Sarah saw her own army adapt."
    new "But with each passing moment, Sarah saw her own army adapt."

    old "Turning away from the breach, soldiers began to turn towards the danger."
    new "Turning away from the breach, soldiers began to turn towards the danger."

    old "Formations reformed and with the layer of archers now mostly dead, the Tribesmen began to encounter the more heavily armored spearmen."
    new "Formations reformed and with the layer of archers now mostly dead, the Tribesmen began to encounter the more heavily armored spearmen."

    old "Sarah watched as the Tribesmen advanced their charge further, driving deeper into her army."
    new "Sarah watched as the Tribesmen advanced their charge further, driving deeper into her army."

    old "But as they did, in turn, the flanks of the Tribesmen themselves began to collapse."
    new "But as they did, in turn, the flanks of the Tribesmen themselves began to collapse."

    old "Her own army closed ranks."
    new "Her own army closed ranks."

    old "The Tribesmen, deadly as they were, were only few in numbers compared to her own army."
    new "The Tribesmen, deadly as they were, were only few in numbers compared to her own army."

    old "Slowly, she watched as her soldiers surrounded the Tribesmen that had advanced into the center of her army."
    new "Slowly, she watched as her soldiers surrounded the Tribesmen that had advanced into the center of her army."

    old "Then, the battle turned again."
    new "Then, the battle turned again."

    old "Having refound their position, her soldiers returned as much as their received."
    new "Having refound their position, her soldiers returned as much as their received."

    old "The Tribesmen were still deadly, inflicting a hard blow, but they were too small in numbers to win."
    new "The Tribesmen were still deadly, inflicting a hard blow, but they were too small in numbers to win."

    old "For every Tribesman that died, likely three of her own soldiers did."
    new "For every Tribesman that died, likely three of her own soldiers did."

    old "But she had the numbers to sustain it."
    new "But she had the numbers to sustain it."

    old "One by one, by lucky spear or arrow, the Tribesmen dwindled down."
    new "One by one, by lucky spear or arrow, the Tribesmen dwindled down."

    old "Until finally, the last few were drowned in the frenzied melee, falling from their horses and dissapearing in the sea of bodies."
    new "Until finally, the last few were drowned in the frenzied melee, falling from their horses and dissapearing in the sea of bodies."

    old "Sarah shuddered at the carnage."
    new "Sarah shuddered at the carnage."

    old "She had won the day, but it had come at a great price."
    new "She had won the day, but it had come at a great price."

    old "The losses she had endured today would be painful."
    new "The losses she had endured today would be painful."

    old "A victory, sure, but she could not endure many more victories like this."
    new "A victory, sure, but she could not endure many more victories like this."

    old "Delay the siege, send scouts"
    new "Delay the siege, send scouts"

    old "I...commander?"
    new "I...commander?"

    old "I said wait. Do not fire yet."
    new "I said wait. Do not fire yet."

    old "Sarah turned to one of her officers."
    new "Sarah turned to one of her officers."

    old "Send two scout units on each end of the city. Ride all the way around and report. Ride in a wide formation."
    new "Send two scout units on each end of the city. Ride all the way around and report. Ride in a wide formation."

    old "The officer saluted and communicated her instructions."
    new "The officer saluted and communicated her instructions."

    old "From a distance, Sarah watched as two regiments of scouts set out from her warcamp."
    new "From a distance, Sarah watched as two regiments of scouts set out from her warcamp."

    old "They moved with great speed, but from such a distance, they appeared slow."
    new "They moved with great speed, but from such a distance, they appeared slow."

    old "Sarah's heart began to beat faster."
    new "Sarah's heart began to beat faster."

    old "Was she just being paranoid? Wasting time she didn't have?"
    new "Was she just being paranoid? Wasting time she didn't have?"

    old "Riding in a wide formation, the scouts spread out and rode further along the city, approaching its flanks."
    new "Riding in a wide formation, the scouts spread out and rode further along the city, approaching its flanks."

    old "Sarah watched a few arrows fly out from the city wall, but they fell aimlessly to the ground. Too far and not nearly accurate enough."
    new "Sarah watched a few arrows fly out from the city wall, but they fell aimlessly to the ground. Too far and not nearly accurate enough."

    old "Suddenly, one of the scouting units drastically changed direction."
    new "Suddenly, one of the scouting units drastically changed direction."

    old "In only a few seconds, they had turned around entirely, rushing back towards the camp."
    new "In only a few seconds, they had turned around entirely, rushing back towards the camp."

    old "Sarah's heart pounded in her chest as she watched their eratic movement."
    new "Sarah's heart pounded in her chest as she watched their eratic movement."

    old "A loud horn blast rang out, signaling danger."
    new "A loud horn blast rang out, signaling danger."

    old "Get ready!"
    new "Get ready!"

    old "Sarah screamed her command."
    new "Sarah screamed her command."

    old "All around her, the army came to life."
    new "All around her, the army came to life."

    old "Already in formation, the soldiers readied their weapons and closed their helmets."
    new "Already in formation, the soldiers readied their weapons and closed their helmets."

    old "The clattering of steel was so loud it drowned out any thought."
    new "The clattering of steel was so loud it drowned out any thought."

    old "Watching from the distance, Sarah saw the snow dust fly up like a storm."
    new "Watching from the distance, Sarah saw the snow dust fly up like a storm."

    old "A great blizzard seemed to form, rushing up behind the fleeing scout unit."
    new "A great blizzard seemed to form, rushing up behind the fleeing scout unit."

    old "But the more she looked, the more Sarah could see it was no force of nature."
    new "But the more she looked, the more Sarah could see it was no force of nature."

    old "The Tribesman."
    new "The Tribesman."

    old "A large unit of Tribesman cavalary was rushing up behind the scouting units."
    new "A large unit of Tribesman cavalary was rushing up behind the scouting units."

    old "There was a distance between the two, but the Tribesmen, being the more skilled riders, were quickly closing the distance."
    new "There was a distance between the two, but the Tribesmen, being the more skilled riders, were quickly closing the distance."

    old "If she wanted to have any hope of saving her men, she needed to take to the field."
    new "If she wanted to have any hope of saving her men, she needed to take to the field."

    old "Moving as one, the front line of the spearmen began to advance."
    new "Moving as one, the front line of the spearmen began to advance."

    old "Their feet, plated in heavy iron, stomped in unison on the ground with each step."
    new "Their feet, plated in heavy iron, stomped in unison on the ground with each step."

    old "Together, they made a dreadful pounding noise, like a hammer struck repeatedly upon a great drum."
    new "Together, they made a dreadful pounding noise, like a hammer struck repeatedly upon a great drum."

    old "In the dsitance, she saw that the Tribesmen had nearly caught up."
    new "In the dsitance, she saw that the Tribesmen had nearly caught up."

    old "But her scouts were so close to the front line."
    new "But her scouts were so close to the front line."

    old "Each only moments away from the other."
    new "Each only moments away from the other."

    old "Then, fate decided, as the Tribesmen proved but a moment too slow."
    new "Then, fate decided, as the Tribesmen proved but a moment too slow."

    old "Sarah watched as her scout regiment ran into her own spearmen frontline."
    new "Sarah watched as her scout regiment ran into her own spearmen frontline."

    old "Trained, experienced, her spearmen lowered their weapons and parted, allowing the scouts to pass through."
    new "Trained, experienced, her spearmen lowered their weapons and parted, allowing the scouts to pass through."

    old "Then, in less than a second, they resumed their position and raised their spears again, closing the gap behind the retreating scouts."
    new "Then, in less than a second, they resumed their position and raised their spears again, closing the gap behind the retreating scouts."

    old "The Tribesmen, so frenzied in their chase, allowed their bloodlust to overtake reason."
    new "The Tribesmen, so frenzied in their chase, allowed their bloodlust to overtake reason."

    old "Sarah watched as the first of the Tribesmen stormed into the frontline of the spearmen."
    new "Sarah watched as the first of the Tribesmen stormed into the frontline of the spearmen."

    old "Caught by great momentum, the bodies of both rider and horse were impaled on the unyielding bulwark of spears."
    new "Caught by great momentum, the bodies of both rider and horse were impaled on the unyielding bulwark of spears."

    old "A great chaotic roar of metal and flesh slamming against one another."
    new "A great chaotic roar of metal and flesh slamming against one another."

    old "And yet, Sarah saw that her frontline held."
    new "And yet, Sarah saw that her frontline held."

    old "Even as the hundreds of Tribesmen stormed into the line. The line held."
    new "Even as the hundreds of Tribesmen stormed into the line. The line held."

    old "The incredible force of the cavalry charged was emptied into the shielded line. They were pushed back one step. Two step."
    new "The incredible force of the cavalry charged was emptied into the shielded line. They were pushed back one step. Two step."

    old "Then, as one and with a thunderous roar, the backline of the spearmen formation pushed up against the frontline."
    new "Then, as one and with a thunderous roar, the backline of the spearmen formation pushed up against the frontline."

    old "And with equally impossible force, the spearmen frontline asserted itself again, pushing forward and throwing the Tribesmen back."
    new "And with equally impossible force, the spearmen frontline asserted itself again, pushing forward and throwing the Tribesmen back."

    old "Their cavalry charge broken on the frontline, their momentum lost."
    new "Their cavalry charge broken on the frontline, their momentum lost."

    old "The remaining Tribesmen considered their options."
    new "The remaining Tribesmen considered their options."

    old "Those that had not charged into the spearmen, had slowed down too much to perform another charge."
    new "Those that had not charged into the spearmen, had slowed down too much to perform another charge."

    old "And even if they could, their fate would be the same."
    new "And even if they could, their fate would be the same."

    old "But they had equally come too close to Sarah's army to simply retreat, fearing a rain of arrows in their back."
    new "But they had equally come too close to Sarah's army to simply retreat, fearing a rain of arrows in their back."

    old "And so, they made the fatal mistake of many a soldier."
    new "And so, they made the fatal mistake of many a soldier."

    old "They doubted."
    new "They doubted."

    old "The rain of arrows that they had feared, came in their moment of hestitation."
    new "The rain of arrows that they had feared, came in their moment of hestitation."

    old "Sarah watched as riders were toppled from their horses, catching arrows to their necks, blood flowing into the white snow."
    new "Sarah watched as riders were toppled from their horses, catching arrows to their necks, blood flowing into the white snow."

